{
  "texts": [
    "eLife has been a well-respected journal in the biomedical sciences since 2012.",
    "In its first decade, it operated on the standard peer-review journal model.",
    "Beginning in 2022 / 2023, it moved to a fundamentally different model where 1) only articles made available on preprint servers are reviewed, 2) peer review is no longer used as a basis to accept / reject an article, and 3) the number of articles published is not artificially limited.",
    "In this model, the decision of whether to host (rather than publish in the classic sense) an article at eLife is made by editors (who are active researchers) prior to peer review, and reviews are presented as commentaries alongside the article.",
    "While this is a significant change in approach, it is not disruptive."
  ]
}